      <body>
         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Monday ¶ Letter dated on the basis of aMS annotation,probably by Shillinglaw, '30 May 76', and the likelihood that the letter was posted the day before this. 29 May 1876 was a Monday. ¶  ¶ In referenc...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">76.05.29</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To John Shillinglaw</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">Box 241/2 Shillinglaw papers, La Trobe Australian manuscripts collection, State Library of Victoria, Melbourne.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style=""/>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn0" n="1">
                  <p rend="FootnoteText"
                     style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>MS black-edged: M's brother-in-law, Eduard Wehl, died on 11 February 1876.</p>
               </note>Monday<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn1" n="2">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Letter dated on the basis of a<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>MS annotation,<space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>probably by Shillinglaw, '30 May 76', and the likelihood that the letter was posted the day before this. 29 May 1876 was a Monday.</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>In reference to the biographic notes, which you desire, dear Mr Shillinglaw, I would suggest that you should honor me with a call, when the exact extent of what seems needful may be fixed, and the form also. You can find me at home any day during day-hours and on Sundays during afternoons. Of course, you know that Sir John Franklin was a Shipmate of Flinders.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn2" n="3">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Shillinglaw was working of a biography of Matthew Flinders, which, however, was never published (ADB).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-size: 12pt; hyphenate: false; "
               xml:lang="en">I can lend you a woodcut of R Brown.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn3" n="4">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                        </seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">A copy of R. Brown (1810)</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>at MEL</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">
                           <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>has a wood</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">-</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">cut of unkn</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">o</seg>
                        <seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="">wn provenance glued to the fly leaf.</seg>
                     </p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
               <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>Sir Rod. Murchison referred to me so gracefully in his annual adress at the RG.S. about 14 or 15 years ago; indeed it may have been earlier.<seg rend="FootnoteReference" style="">
                  <note type="footnote" xml:id="_ftn4" n="5">
                     <p rend="FootnoteText"
                        style="margin-left: 0.3333in; text-indent: -0.3333in; font-size: 9pt; hyphenate: false; "
                        xml:lang="en">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Murchison in an address to the Royal Geographical Society on 23 May 1859 noted that 'Dr Mueller, on whose shoulders as an Australian botanist has fallen the mantle of Robert Brown, is continually issuing new works on the plants of the continent, whether those which he collected in tropical or northern Australia, when he was the companion of Gregory, or those of Victoria' (<seg rend="DefaultParagraphFont" style="font-style: italic; ">Proceedings of the Royal Geographical Society</seg>, vol. 3 [1858-9], p. 342).</p>
                  </note>
               </seg>
            </p>
         </div>
      </body>
